CONTRIBUTING.md
     1â†’# Contributing
     2â†’
     3â†’1. [Fork it](https://help.github.com/articles/fork-a-repo/)
     4â†’2. Install dependencies (`npm install`)
     5â†’3. Create your feature branch (`git checkout -b my-new-feature`)
     6â†’4. Commit your changes (`git commit -am 'Added some feature'`)
     7â†’5. Test your changes (`npm test`)
     8â†’6. Push to the branch (`git push origin my-new-feature`)
     9â†’7. [Create new Pull Request](https://help.github.com/articles/creating-a-pull-request/)
    10â†’
    11â†’## Testing
    12â†’
    13â†’We use [TAP](https://github.com/tapjs/node-tap) to write tests. Run our test suite with this command:
    14â†’
    15â†’```
    16â†’npm test
    17â†’```
    18â†’
    19â†’## Code Style
    20â†’
    21â†’We use [standard](https://www.npmjs.com/package/standard) and [editorconfig](http://editorconfig.org) to maintain code style and best practices. Please make sure your PR adheres to the guides by running:
    22â†’
    23â†’```
    24â†’npm run lint
    25â†’```
README-es.md
     1â†’# dotenv [![NPM version](https://img.shields.io/npm/v/dotenv.svg?style=flat-square)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dotenv) [![downloads](https://img.shields.io/npm/dw/dotenv)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dotenv)
     2â†’
     3â†’<img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/motdotla/dotenv/master/dotenv.svg" alt="dotenv" align="right" width="200" />
     4â†’
     5â†’Dotenv is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a `.env` file into [`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env). Storing configuration in the environment separate from code is based on [The Twelve-Factor App](https://12factor.net/config) methodology.
     6â†’
     7â†’[Watch the tutorial](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtkZR0NFd1g)
     8â†’
     9â†’&nbsp;
    10â†’
    11â†’## Usage
    12â†’
    13â†’Install it.
    14â†’
    15â†’```sh
    16â†’npm install dotenv --save
    17â†’```
    18â†’
    19â†’Create a `.env` file in the root of your project:
    20â†’
    21â†’```ini
    22â†’# .env
    23â†’S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    24â†’SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    25â†’```
    26â†’
    27â†’And as early as possible in your application, import and configure dotenv:
    28â†’
    29â†’```javascript
    30â†’require('dotenv').config() // or import 'dotenv/config' if you're using ES6
    31â†’...
    32â†’console.log(process.env) // remove this after you've confirmed it is working
    33â†’```
    34â†’
    35â†’That's it. `process.env` now has the keys and values you defined in your `.env` file:
    36â†’
    37â†’&nbsp;
    38â†’
    39â†’## Advanced
    40â†’
    41â†’<details><summary>ES6</summary><br>
    42â†’
    43â†’Import with [ES6](#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import):
    44â†’
    45â†’```javascript
    46â†’import 'dotenv/config'
    47â†’```
    48â†’
    49â†’ES6 import if you need to set config options:
    50â†’
    51â†’```javascript
    52â†’import dotenv from 'dotenv'
    53â†’dotenv.config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
    54â†’```
    55â†’
    56â†’</details>
    57â†’<details><summary>bun</summary><br>
    58â†’
    59â†’```sh
    60â†’bun add dotenv
    61â†’```
    62â†’
    63â†’</details>
    64â†’<details><summary>yarn</summary><br>
    65â†’
    66â†’```sh
    67â†’yarn add dotenv
    68â†’```
    69â†’
    70â†’</details>
    71â†’<details><summary>pnpm</summary><br>
    72â†’
    73â†’```sh
    74â†’pnpm add dotenv
    75â†’```
    76â†’
    77â†’</details>
    78â†’<details><summary>Monorepos</summary><br>
    79â†’
    80â†’For monorepos with a structure like `apps/backend/app.js`, put it the `.env` file in the root of the folder where your `app.js` process runs.
    81â†’
    82â†’```ini
    83â†’# app/backend/.env
    84â†’S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    85â†’SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    86â†’```
    87â†’
    88â†’</details>
    89â†’<details><summary>Multiline Values</summary><br>
    90â†’
    91â†’If you need multiline variables, for example private keys, those are now supported (`>= v15.0.0`) with line breaks:
    92â†’
    93â†’```ini
    94â†’PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
    95â†’...
    96â†’Kh9NV...
    97â†’...
    98â†’-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----"
    99â†’```
   100â†’
   101â†’Alternatively, you can double quote strings and use the `\n` character:
   102â†’
   103â†’```ini
   104â†’PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\nKh9NV...\n-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
   105â†’```
   106â†’
   107â†’</details>
   108â†’<details><summary>Comments</summary><br>
   109â†’
   110â†’Comments may be added to your file on their own line or inline:
   111â†’
   112â†’```ini
   113â†’# This is a comment
   114â†’SECRET_KEY=YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE # comment
   115â†’SECRET_HASH="something-with-a-#-hash"
   116â†’```
   117â†’
   118â†’Comments begin where a `#` exists, so if your value contains a `#` please wrap it in quotes. This is a breaking change from `>= v15.0.0` and on.
   119â†’
   120â†’</details>
   121â†’<details><summary>Parsing</summary><br>
   122â†’
   123â†’The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   124â†’
   125â†’```javascript
   126â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   127â†’const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   128â†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   129â†’console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   130â†’```
   131â†’
   132â†’</details>
   133â†’<details><summary>Preload</summary><br>
   134â†’
   135â†’> Note: Consider using [`dotenvx`](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) instead of preloading. I am now doing (and recommending) so.
   136â†’>
   137â†’> It serves the same purpose (you do not need to require and load dotenv), adds better debugging, and works with ANY language, framework, or platform. â€“ [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   138â†’
   139â†’You can use the `--require` (`-r`) [command line option](https://nodejs.org/api/cli.html#-r---require-module) to preload dotenv. By doing this, you do not need to require and load dotenv in your application code.
   140â†’
   141â†’```bash
   142â†’$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   143â†’```
   144â†’
   145â†’The configuration options below are supported as command line arguments in the format `dotenv_config_<option>=value`
   146â†’
   147â†’```bash
   148â†’$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env dotenv_config_debug=true
   149â†’```
   150â†’
   151â†’Additionally, you can use environment variables to set configuration options. Command line arguments will precede these.
   152â†’
   153â†’```bash
   154â†’$ DOTENV_CONFIG_<OPTION>=value node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   155â†’```
   156â†’
   157â†’```bash
   158â†’$ DOTENV_CONFIG_ENCODING=latin1 DOTENV_CONFIG_DEBUG=true node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env
   159â†’```
   160â†’
   161â†’</details>
   162â†’<details><summary>Variable Expansion</summary><br>
   163â†’
   164â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for variable expansion.
   165â†’
   166â†’Reference and expand variables already on your machine for use in your .env file.
   167â†’
   168â†’```ini
   169â†’# .env
   170â†’USERNAME="username"
   171â†’DATABASE_URL="postgres://${USERNAME}@localhost/my_database"
   172â†’```
   173â†’```js
   174â†’// index.js
   175â†’console.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   176â†’```
   177â†’```sh
   178â†’$ dotenvx run --debug -- node index.js
   179â†’[dotenvx@0.14.1] injecting env (2) from .env
   180â†’DATABASE_URL postgres://username@localhost/my_database
   181â†’```
   182â†’
   183â†’</details>
   184â†’<details><summary>Command Substitution</summary><br>
   185â†’
   186â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for command substitution.
   187â†’
   188â†’Add the output of a command to one of your variables in your .env file.
   189â†’
   190â†’```ini
   191â†’# .env
   192â†’DATABASE_URL="postgres://$(whoami)@localhost/my_database"
   193â†’```
   194â†’```js
   195â†’// index.js
   196â†’console.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   197â†’```
   198â†’```sh
   199â†’$ dotenvx run --debug -- node index.js
   200â†’[dotenvx@0.14.1] injecting env (1) from .env
   201â†’DATABASE_URL postgres://yourusername@localhost/my_database
   202â†’```
   203â†’
   204â†’</details>
   205â†’<details><summary>Encryption</summary><br>
   206â†’
   207â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for encryption.
   208â†’
   209â†’Add encryption to your `.env` files with a single command.
   210â†’
   211â†’```
   212â†’$ dotenvx set HELLO Production -f .env.production
   213â†’$ echo "console.log('Hello ' + process.env.HELLO)" > index.js
   214â†’
   215â†’$ DOTENV_PRIVATE_KEY_PRODUCTION="<.env.production private key>" dotenvx run -- node index.js
   216â†’[dotenvx] injecting env (2) from .env.production
   217â†’Hello Production
   218â†’```
   219â†’
   220â†’[learn more](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx?tab=readme-ov-file#encryption)
   221â†’
   222â†’</details>
   223â†’<details><summary>Multiple Environments</summary><br>
   224â†’
   225â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to manage multiple environments.
   226â†’
   227â†’Run any environment locally. Create a `.env.ENVIRONMENT` file and use `-f` to load it. It's straightforward, yet flexible.
   228â†’
   229â†’```bash
   230â†’$ echo "HELLO=production" > .env.production
   231â†’$ echo "console.log('Hello ' + process.env.HELLO)" > index.js
   232â†’
   233â†’$ dotenvx run -f=.env.production -- node index.js
   234â†’Hello production
   235â†’> ^^
   236â†’```
   237â†’
   238â†’or with multiple .env files
   239â†’
   240â†’```bash
   241â†’$ echo "HELLO=local" > .env.local
   242â†’$ echo "HELLO=World" > .env
   243â†’$ echo "console.log('Hello ' + process.env.HELLO)" > index.js
   244â†’
   245â†’$ dotenvx run -f=.env.local -f=.env -- node index.js
   246â†’Hello local
   247â†’```
   248â†’
   249â†’[more environment examples](https://dotenvx.com/docs/quickstart/environments)
   250â†’
   251â†’</details>
   252â†’<details><summary>Production</summary><br>
   253â†’
   254â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for production deploys.
   255â†’
   256â†’Create a `.env.production` file.
   257â†’
   258â†’```sh
   259â†’$ echo "HELLO=production" > .env.production
   260â†’```
   261â†’
   262â†’Encrypt it.
   263â†’
   264â†’```sh
   265â†’$ dotenvx encrypt -f .env.production
   266â†’```
   267â†’
   268â†’Set `DOTENV_PRIVATE_KEY_PRODUCTION` (found in `.env.keys`) on your server.
   269â†’
   270â†’```
   271â†’$ heroku config:set DOTENV_PRIVATE_KEY_PRODUCTION=value
   272â†’```
   273â†’
   274â†’Commit your `.env.production` file to code and deploy.
   275â†’
   276â†’```
   277â†’$ git add .env.production
   278â†’$ git commit -m "encrypted .env.production"
   279â†’$ git push heroku main
   280â†’```
   281â†’
   282â†’Dotenvx will decrypt and inject the secrets at runtime using `dotenvx run -- node index.js`.
   283â†’
   284â†’</details>
   285â†’<details><summary>Syncing</summary><br>
   286â†’
   287â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to sync your .env files.
   288â†’
   289â†’Encrypt them with `dotenvx encrypt -f .env` and safely include them in source control. Your secrets are securely synced with your git.
   290â†’
   291â†’This still subscribes to the twelve-factor app rules by generating a decryption key separate from code.
   292â†’
   293â†’</details>
   294â†’<details><summary>More Examples</summary><br>
   295â†’
   296â†’See [examples](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples) of using dotenv with various frameworks, languages, and configurations.
   297â†’
   298â†’* [nodejs](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-nodejs)
   299â†’* [nodejs (debug on)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-nodejs-debug)
   300â†’* [nodejs (override on)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-nodejs-override)
   301â†’* [nodejs (processEnv override)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-custom-target)
   302â†’* [esm](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-esm)
   303â†’* [esm (preload)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-esm-preload)
   304â†’* [typescript](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-typescript)
   305â†’* [typescript parse](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-typescript-parse)
   306â†’* [typescript config](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-typescript-config)
   307â†’* [webpack](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-webpack)
