   318â†’
   319â†’## Agentes
   320â†’
   321â†’<img src="https://dotenvx.com/assets/img/as2/9.jpg" height="400" alt="dotenvx-as2" align="right"/>
   322â†’
   323â†’> El software estأ، cambiando, y dotenv debe cambiar con أ©lâ€”por eso construأ­ [agentic secret storage (AS2)](https://dotenvx.com/as2). Los agentes ejecutan cأ³digo sin humanos en la terminal, por lo que los archivos `.env` en texto plano son el primitivo equivocado.
   324â†’>
   325â†’> AS2 estأ، diseأ±ado para software autأ³nomo: cifrado por defecto, cero acceso a consola y entrega priorizando la criptografأ­a que mantiene a los operadores fuera del circuito.
   326â†’>
   327â†’> Estأ، respaldado por [Vestauth](https://github.com/vestauth/vestauth), la capa de autenticaciأ³n pionera y de confianza para agentesâ€”que otorga a cada agente una identidad criptogrأ،fica para firmar solicitudes con claves privadas y verificarlas con claves pأ؛blicas. Sin secretos compartidos que se filtren.
   328â†’>
   329â†’> Es lo que uso ahora. - [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   330â†’
   331â†’### Inicio rأ،pido
   332â†’
   333â†’Instala vestauth e inicializa tu agente.
   334â†’
   335â†’```bash
   336â†’npm i -g vestauth
   337â†’
   338â†’vestauth agent init
   339â†’```
   340â†’
   341â†’Tu agente puede `set` secretos con un endpoint `curl` simple:
   342â†’
   343â†’```bash
   344â†’vestauth agent curl -X POST https://as2.dotenvx.com/set -d '{"KEY":"value"}'
   345â†’```
   346â†’
   347â†’Y tu agente puede `get` secretos con un endpoint `curl` simple:
   348â†’
   349â†’```bash
   350â†’vestauth agent curl "https://as2.dotenvx.com/get?key=KEY"
   351â†’```
   352â†’
   353â†’آ،Eso es todo! Este nuevo primitivo habilita el acceso a secretos para agentes sin intervenciأ³n humana, flujos de OAuth ni claves API. Es el futuro para los agentes.
   354â†’
   355â†’&nbsp;
   356â†’
   357â†’## FAQ
   358â†’
   359â†’<details><summary>Should I commit my `.env` file?</summary><br/>
   360â†’
   361â†’No.
   362â†’
   363â†’Unless you encrypt it with [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx). Then we recommend you do.
   364â†’
   365â†’</details>
   366â†’<details><summary>What about variable expansion?</summary><br/>
   367â†’
   368â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx).
   369â†’
   370â†’</details>
   371â†’<details><summary>Should I have multiple `.env` files?</summary><br/>
   372â†’
   373â†’We recommend creating one `.env` file per environment. Use `.env` for local/development, `.env.production` for production and so on. This still follows the twelve factor principles as each is attributed individually to its own environment. Avoid custom set ups that work in inheritance somehow (`.env.production` inherits values form `.env` for example). It is better to duplicate values if necessary across each `.env.environment` file.
   374â†’
   375â†’> In a twelve-factor app, env vars are granular controls, each fully orthogonal to other env vars. They are never grouped together as â€œenvironmentsâ€‌, but instead are independently managed for each deploy. This is a model that scales up smoothly as the app naturally expands into more deploys over its lifetime.
   376â†’>
   377â†’> â€“ [The Twelve-Factor App](http://12factor.net/config)
   378â†’
   379â†’Additionally, we recommend using [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to encrypt and manage these.
   380â†’
   381â†’</details>
   382â†’
   383â†’<details><summary>How do I use dotenv with `import`?</summary><br/>
   384â†’
   385â†’Simply..
   386â†’
   387â†’```javascript
   388â†’// index.mjs (ESM)
   389â†’import 'dotenv/config' // see https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import
   390â†’import express from 'express'
   391â†’```
   392â†’
   393â†’A little background..
   394â†’
   395â†’> When you run a module containing an `import` declaration, the modules it imports are loaded first, then each module body is executed in a depth-first traversal of the dependency graph, avoiding cycles by skipping anything already executed.
   396â†’>
   397â†’> â€“ [ES6 In Depth: Modules](https://hacks.mozilla.org/2015/08/es6-in-depth-modules/)
   398â†’
   399â†’What does this mean in plain language? It means you would think the following would work but it won't.
   400â†’
   401â†’`errorReporter.mjs`:
   402â†’```js
   403â†’class Client {
   404â†’  constructor (apiKey) {
   405â†’    console.log('apiKey', apiKey)
   406â†’
   407â†’    this.apiKey = apiKey
   408â†’  }
   409â†’}
   410â†’
   411â†’export default new Client(process.env.API_KEY)
   412â†’```
   413â†’`index.mjs`:
   414â†’```js
   415â†’// Note: this is INCORRECT and will not work
   416â†’import * as dotenv from 'dotenv'
   417â†’dotenv.config()
   418â†’
   419â†’import errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs' // process.env.API_KEY will be blank!
   420â†’```
   421â†’
   422â†’`process.env.API_KEY` will be blank.
   423â†’
   424â†’Instead, `index.mjs` should be written as..
   425â†’
   426â†’```js
   427â†’import 'dotenv/config'
   428â†’
   429â†’import errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs'
   430â†’```
   431â†’
   432â†’Does that make sense? It's a bit unintuitive, but it is how importing of ES6 modules work. Here is a [working example of this pitfall](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-es6-import-pitfall).
   433â†’
   434â†’There are two alternatives to this approach:
   435â†’
   436â†’1. Preload with dotenvx: `dotenvx run -- node index.js` (_Note: you do not need to `import` dotenv with this approach_)
   437â†’2. Create a separate file that will execute `config` first as outlined in [this comment on #133](https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv/issues/133#issuecomment-255298822)
   438â†’</details>
   439â†’
   440â†’<details><summary>Can I customize/write plugins for dotenv?</summary><br/>
   441â†’
   442â†’Yes! `dotenv.config()` returns an object representing the parsed `.env` file. This gives you everything you need to continue setting values on `process.env`. For example:
   443â†’
   444â†’```js
   445â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   446â†’const variableExpansion = require('dotenv-expand')
   447â†’const myEnv = dotenv.config()
   448â†’variableExpansion(myEnv)
   449â†’```
   450â†’
   451â†’</details>
   452â†’<details><summary>What rules does the parsing engine follow?</summary><br/>
   453â†’
   454â†’The parsing engine currently supports the following rules:
   455â†’
   456â†’- `BASIC=basic` becomes `{BASIC: 'basic'}`
   457â†’- empty lines are skipped
   458â†’- lines beginning with `#` are treated as comments
   459â†’- `#` marks the beginning of a comment (unless when the value is wrapped in quotes)
   460â†’- empty values become empty strings (`EMPTY=` becomes `{EMPTY: ''}`)
   461â†’- inner quotes are maintained (think JSON) (`JSON={"foo": "bar"}` becomes `{JSON:"{\"foo\": \"bar\"}"`)
   462â†’- whitespace is removed from both ends of unquoted values (see more on [`trim`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/Trim)) (`FOO=  some value  ` becomes `{FOO: 'some value'}`)
   463â†’- single and double quoted values are escaped (`SINGLE_QUOTE='quoted'` becomes `{SINGLE_QUOTE: "quoted"}`)
   464â†’- single and double quoted values maintain whitespace from both ends (`FOO="  some value  "` becomes `{FOO: '  some value  '}`)
   465â†’- double quoted values expand new lines (`MULTILINE="new\nline"` becomes
   466â†’
   467â†’```
   468â†’{MULTILINE: 'new
   469â†’line'}
   470â†’```
   471â†’
   472â†’- backticks are supported (`` BACKTICK_KEY=`This has 'single' and "double" quotes inside of it.` ``)
   473â†’
   474â†’</details>
   475â†’<details><summary>What about syncing and securing .env files?</summary><br/>
   476â†’
   477â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to unlock syncing encrypted .env files over git.
   478â†’
   479â†’</details>
   480â†’<details><summary>What if I accidentally commit my `.env` file to code?</summary><br/>
   481â†’
   482â†’Remove it, [remove git history](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/removing-sensitive-data-from-a-repository) and then install the [git pre-commit hook](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx#pre-commit) to prevent this from ever happening again. 
   483â†’
   484â†’```
   485â†’npm i -g @dotenvx/dotenvx
   486â†’dotenvx precommit --install
   487â†’```
   488â†’
   489â†’</details>
   490â†’<details><summary>What happens to environment variables that were already set?</summary><br/>
   491â†’
   492â†’By default, we will never modify any environment variables that have already been set. In particular, if there is a variable in your `.env` file which collides with one that already exists in your environment, then that variable will be skipped.
   493â†’
   494â†’If instead, you want to override `process.env` use the `override` option.
   495â†’
   496â†’```javascript
   497â†’require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   498â†’```
   499â†’
   500â†’</details>
   501â†’<details><summary>How can I prevent committing my `.env` file to a Docker build?</summary><br/>
   502â†’
   503â†’Use the [docker prebuild hook](https://dotenvx.com/docs/features/prebuild).
   504â†’
   505â†’```bash
   506â†’# Dockerfile
   507â†’...
   508â†’RUN curl -fsS https://dotenvx.sh/ | sh
   509â†’...
   510â†’RUN dotenvx prebuild
   511â†’CMD ["dotenvx", "run", "--", "node", "index.js"]
   512â†’```
   513â†’
   514â†’</details>
   515â†’<details><summary>How come my environment variables are not showing up for React?</summary><br/>
   516â†’
   517â†’Your React code is run in Webpack, where the `fs` module or even the `process` global itself are not accessible out-of-the-box. `process.env` can only be injected through Webpack configuration.
   518â†’
   519â†’If you are using [`react-scripts`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/react-scripts), which is distributed through [`create-react-app`](https://create-react-app.dev/), it has dotenv built in but with a quirk. Preface your environment variables with `REACT_APP_`. See [this stack overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42182577/is-it-possible-to-use-dotenv-in-a-react-project) for more details.
   520â†’
   521â†’If you are using other frameworks (e.g. Next.js, Gatsby...), you need to consult their documentation for how to inject environment variables into the client.
   522â†’
   523â†’</details>
   524â†’<details><summary>Why is the `.env` file not loading my environment variables successfully?</summary><br/>
   525â†’
   526â†’Most likely your `.env` file is not in the correct place. [See this stack overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42335016/dotenv-file-is-not-loading-environment-variables).
   527â†’
   528â†’Turn on debug mode and try again..
   529â†’
   530â†’```js
   531â†’require('dotenv').config({ debug: true })
   532â†’```
   533â†’
   534â†’You will receive a helpful error outputted to your console.
   535â†’
   536â†’</details>
   537â†’<details><summary>Why am I getting the error `Module not found: Error: Can't resolve 'crypto|os|path'`?</summary><br/>
   538â†’
   539â†’You are using dotenv on the front-end and have not included a polyfill. Webpack < 5 used to include these for you. Do the following:
   540â†’
   541â†’```bash
   542â†’npm install node-polyfill-webpack-plugin
   543â†’```
   544â†’
   545â†’Configure your `webpack.config.js` to something like the following.
   546â†’
   547â†’```js
   548â†’require('dotenv').config()
   549â†’
   550â†’const path = require('path');
   551â†’const webpack = require('webpack')
   552â†’
   553â†’const NodePolyfillPlugin = require('node-polyfill-webpack-plugin')
   554â†’
   555â†’module.exports = {
   556â†’  mode: 'development',
   557â†’  entry: './src/index.ts',
   558â†’  output: {
   559â†’    filename: 'bundle.js',
   560â†’    path: path.resolve(__dirname, 'dist'),
   561â†’  },
   562â†’  plugins: [
   563â†’    new NodePolyfillPlugin(),
   564â†’    new webpack.DefinePlugin({
   565â†’      'process.env': {
   566â†’        HELLO: JSON.stringify(process.env.HELLO)
   567â†’      }
   568â†’    }),
   569â†’  ]
   570â†’};
   571â†’```
   572â†’
   573â†’Alternatively, just use [dotenv-webpack](https://github.com/mrsteele/dotenv-webpack) which does this and more behind the scenes for you.
   574â†’
   575â†’</details>
   576â†’
   577â†’&nbsp;
   578â†’
   579â†’## Docs
   580â†’
   581â†’Dotenv exposes four functions:
   582â†’
   583â†’* `config`
   584â†’* `parse`
   585â†’* `populate`
   586â†’
   587â†’### Config
   588â†’
   589â†’`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590â†’[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591â†’and return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592â†’
   593â†’```js
   594â†’const result = dotenv.config()
   595â†’
   596â†’if (result.error) {
   597â†’  throw result.error
   598â†’}
   599â†’
   600â†’console.log(result.parsed)
   601â†’```
   602â†’
   603â†’You can additionally, pass options to `config`.
   604â†’
   605â†’#### Options
   606â†’
   607â†’##### path
   608â†’
   609â†’Default: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610â†’
   611â†’Specify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612â†’
   613â†’```js
   614â†’require('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615â†’```
   616â†’
   617â†’By default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618â†’
   619â†’Pass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620â†’
   621â†’```js  
   622â†’require('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623â†’```
   624â†’
   625â†’##### quiet
   626â†’
   627â†’Default: `false`
   628â†’
   629â†’Suppress runtime logging message.
   630â†’
   631â†’```js
   632â†’// index.js
   633â†’require('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634â†’console.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635â†’```
   636â†’
   637â†’```ini
   638â†’# .env
   639â†’HELLO=World
   640â†’```
   641â†’
   642â†’```sh
   643â†’$ node index.js
   644â†’[dotenv@17.0.0] injecting env (1) from .env
   645â†’Hello World
   646â†’```
   647â†’
   648â†’##### encoding
   649â†’
   650â†’Default: `utf8`
   651â†’
   652â†’Specify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653â†’
   654â†’```js
   655â†’require('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656â†’```
   657â†’
   658â†’##### debug
   659â†’
   660â†’Default: `false`
   661â†’
   662â†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663â†’
   664â†’```js
   665â†’require('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666â†’```
   667â†’
   668â†’##### override
   669â†’
   670â†’Default: `false`
   671â†’
   672â†’Override any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673â†’
   674â†’```js
   675â†’require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676â†’```
   677â†’
   678â†’##### processEnv
   679â†’
   680â†’Default: `process.env`
   681â†’
   682â†’Specify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683â†’
   684â†’```js
   685â†’const myObject = {}
   686â†’require('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687â†’
   688â†’console.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689â†’console.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690â†’```
   691â†’
   692â†’### Parse
   693â†’
   694â†’The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695â†’variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696â†’an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697â†’
   698â†’```js
   699â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700â†’const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701â†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702â†’console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703â†’```
   704â†’
   705â†’#### Options
   706â†’
   707â†’##### debug
   708â†’
   709â†’Default: `false`
   710â†’
   711â†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712â†’
   713â†’```js
   714â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715â†’const buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716â†’const opt = { debug: true }
   717â†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718â†’// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719â†’```
   720â†’
   721â†’### Populate
   722â†’
   723â†’The engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724â†’
   725â†’For example, customizing the source:
   726â†’
   727â†’```js
   728â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729â†’const parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730â†’
   731â†’dotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732â†’
   733â†’console.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
   734â†’```
   735â†’
   736â†’For example, customizing the source AND target:
   737â†’
   738â†’```js
   739â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   740â†’const parsed = { HELLO: 'universe' }
   741â†’const target = { HELLO: 'world' } // empty object
   742â†’
   743â†’dotenv.populate(target, parsed, { override: true, debug: true })
   744â†’
   745â†’console.log(target) // { HELLO: 'universe' }
   746â†’```
   747â†’
   748â†’#### options
   749â†’
   750â†’##### Debug
   751â†’
   752â†’Default: `false`
   753â†’
   754â†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755â†’
   756â†’##### override
   757â†’
   758â†’Default: `false`
   759â†’
   760â†’Override any environment variables that have already been set.
   761â†’
   762â†’&nbsp;
   763â†’
   764â†’## CHANGELOG
   765â†’
   766â†’See [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md)
   767â†’
   768â†’&nbsp;
   769â†’
   770â†’## Who's using dotenv?
   771â†’
   772â†’[These npm modules depend on it.](https://www.npmjs.com/browse/depended/dotenv)
   773â†’
   774â†’Projects that expand it often use the [keyword "dotenv" on npm](https://www.npmjs.com/search?q=keywords:dotenv).
README.md
     1â†’# dotenv [![NPM version](https://img.shields.io/npm/v/dotenv.svg?style=flat-square)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dotenv) [![downloads](https://img.shields.io/npm/dw/dotenv)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/dotenv)
     2â†’
     3â†’<img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/motdotla/dotenv/master/dotenv.svg" alt="dotenv" align="right" width="200" />
     4â†’
     5â†’Dotenv is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a `.env` file into [`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env). Storing configuration in the environment separate from code is based on [The Twelve-Factor App](https://12factor.net/config) methodology.
     6â†’
     7â†’[Watch the tutorial](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtkZR0NFd1g)
     8â†’
     9â†’&nbsp;
    10â†’
    11â†’## Usage
    12â†’
    13â†’Install it.
    14â†’
    15â†’```sh
    16â†’npm install dotenv --save
    17â†’```
    18â†’
    19â†’Create a `.env` file in the root of your project:
    20â†’
    21â†’```ini
    22â†’# .env
    23â†’S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    24â†’SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    25â†’```
    26â†’
    27â†’And as early as possible in your application, import and configure dotenv:
    28â†’
    29â†’```javascript
    30â†’require('dotenv').config() // or import 'dotenv/config' if you're using ES6
    31â†’...
    32â†’console.log(process.env) // remove this after you've confirmed it is working
    33â†’```
    34â†’
    35â†’That's it. `process.env` now has the keys and values you defined in your `.env` file:
    36â†’
    37â†’&nbsp;
    38â†’
    39â†’## Advanced
    40â†’
    41â†’<details><summary>ES6</summary><br>
    42â†’
    43â†’Import with [ES6](#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import):
    44â†’
    45â†’```javascript
    46â†’import 'dotenv/config'
    47â†’```
    48â†’
    49â†’ES6 import if you need to set config options:
    50â†’
    51â†’```javascript
    52â†’import dotenv from 'dotenv'
    53â†’dotenv.config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
    54â†’```
    55â†’
    56â†’</details>
    57â†’<details><summary>bun</summary><br>
    58â†’
    59â†’```sh
    60â†’bun add dotenv
    61â†’```
    62â†’
    63â†’</details>
    64â†’<details><summary>yarn</summary><br>
    65â†’
    66â†’```sh
    67â†’yarn add dotenv
    68â†’```
    69â†’
    70â†’</details>
    71â†’<details><summary>pnpm</summary><br>
    72â†’
    73â†’```sh
    74â†’pnpm add dotenv
    75â†’```
    76â†’
    77â†’</details>
    78â†’<details><summary>Monorepos</summary><br>
    79â†’
    80â†’For monorepos with a structure like `apps/backend/app.js`, put it the `.env` file in the root of the folder where your `app.js` process runs.
    81â†’
    82â†’```ini
    83â†’# app/backend/.env
    84â†’S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    85â†’SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    86â†’```
    87â†’
    88â†’</details>
    89â†’<details><summary>Multiline Values</summary><br>
    90â†’
    91â†’If you need multiline variables, for example private keys, those are now supported (`>= v15.0.0`) with line breaks:
    92â†’
    93â†’```ini
    94â†’PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
    95â†’...
    96â†’Kh9NV...
    97â†’...
    98â†’-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----"
    99â†’```
   100â†’
   101â†’Alternatively, you can double quote strings and use the `\n` character:
   102â†’
   103â†’```ini
   104â†’PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\nKh9NV...\n-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
   105â†’```
   106â†’
   107â†’</details>
   108â†’<details><summary>Comments</summary><br>
   109â†’
   110â†’Comments may be added to your file on their own line or inline:
   111â†’
   112â†’```ini
   113â†’# This is a comment
   114â†’SECRET_KEY=YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE # comment
   115â†’SECRET_HASH="something-with-a-#-hash"
   116â†’```
   117â†’
   118â†’Comments begin where a `#` exists, so if your value contains a `#` please wrap it in quotes. This is a breaking change from `>= v15.0.0` and on.
   119â†’
   120â†’</details>
   121â†’<details><summary>Parsing</summary><br>
   122â†’
   123â†’The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   124â†’
   125â†’```javascript
   126â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   127â†’const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   128â†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   129â†’console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   130â†’```
   131â†’
   132â†’</details>
   133â†’<details><summary>Preload</summary><br>
   134â†’
   135â†’> Note: Consider using [`dotenvx`](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) instead of preloading. I am now doing (and recommending) so.
   136â†’>
   137â†’> It serves the same purpose (you do not need to require and load dotenv), adds better debugging, and works with ANY language, framework, or platform. â€“ [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   138â†’
   139â†’You can use the `--require` (`-r`) [command line option](https://nodejs.org/api/cli.html#-r---require-module) to preload dotenv. By doing this, you do not need to require and load dotenv in your application code.
   140â†’
   141â†’```bash
   142â†’$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   143â†’```
   144â†’
   145â†’The configuration options below are supported as command line arguments in the format `dotenv_config_<option>=value`
   146â†’
   147â†’```bash
   148â†’$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env dotenv_config_debug=true
   149â†’```
   150â†’
   151â†’Additionally, you can use environment variables to set configuration options. Command line arguments will precede these.
   152â†’
   153â†’```bash
   154â†’$ DOTENV_CONFIG_<OPTION>=value node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   155â†’```
   156â†’
   157â†’```bash
   158â†’$ DOTENV_CONFIG_ENCODING=latin1 DOTENV_CONFIG_DEBUG=true node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env
   159â†’```
   160â†’
   161â†’</details>
   162â†’<details><summary>Variable Expansion</summary><br>
   163â†’
   164â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for variable expansion.
   165â†’
   166â†’Reference and expand variables already on your machine for use in your .env file.
   167â†’
   168â†’```ini
   169â†’# .env
   170â†’USERNAME="username"
   171â†’DATABASE_URL="postgres://${USERNAME}@localhost/my_database"
   172â†’```
   173â†’```js
   174â†’// index.js
   175â†’console.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   176â†’```
   177â†’```sh
   178â†’$ dotenvx run --debug -- node index.js
   179â†’[dotenvx@0.14.1] injecting env (2) from .env
   180â†’DATABASE_URL postgres://username@localhost/my_database
   181â†’```
   182â†’
   183â†’</details>
   184â†’<details><summary>Command Substitution</summary><br>
   185â†’
   186â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for command substitution.
   187â†’
   188â†’Add the output of a command to one of your variables in your .env file.
   189â†’
   190â†’```ini
   191â†’# .env
   192â†’DATABASE_URL="postgres://$(whoami)@localhost/my_database"
   193â†’```
   194â†’```js
   195â†’// index.js
   196â†’console.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   197â†’```
   198â†’```sh
   199â†’$ dotenvx run --debug -- node index.js
   200â†’[dotenvx@0.14.1] injecting env (1) from .env
   201â†’DATABASE_URL postgres://yourusername@localhost/my_database
   202â†’```
   203â†’
   204â†’</details>
   205â†’<details><summary>Encryption</summary><br>
   206â†’
   207â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for encryption.
   208â†’
   209â†’Add encryption to your `.env` files with a single command.
   210â†’
   211â†’```
   212â†’$ dotenvx set HELLO Production -f .env.production
   213â†’$ echo "console.log('Hello ' + process.env.HELLO)" > index.js
   214â†’
   215â†’$ DOTENV_PRIVATE_KEY_PRODUCTION="<.env.production private key>" dotenvx run -- node index.js
   216â†’[dotenvx] injecting env (2) from .env.production
   217â†’Hello Production
   218â†’```
   219â†’
   220â†’[learn more](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx?tab=readme-ov-file#encryption)
   221â†’
   222â†’</details>
   223â†’<details><summary>Multiple Environments</summary><br>
   224â†’
   225â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to manage multiple environments.
   226â†’
   227â†’Run any environment locally. Create a `.env.ENVIRONMENT` file and use `-f` to load it. It's straightforward, yet flexible.
   228â†’
   229â†’```bash
   230â†’$ echo "HELLO=production" > .env.production
   231â†’$ echo "console.log('Hello ' + process.env.HELLO)" > index.js
   232â†’
   233â†’$ dotenvx run -f=.env.production -- node index.js
   234â†’Hello production
   235â†’> ^^
   236â†’```
   237â†’
   238â†’or with multiple .env files
   239â†’
   240â†’```bash
   241â†’$ echo "HELLO=local" > .env.local
   242â†’$ echo "HELLO=World" > .env
   243â†’$ echo "console.log('Hello ' + process.env.HELLO)" > index.js
   244â†’
   245â†’$ dotenvx run -f=.env.local -f=.env -- node index.js
   246â†’Hello local
   247â†’```
   248â†’
   249â†’[more environment examples](https://dotenvx.com/docs/quickstart/environments)
   250â†’
   251â†’</details>
   252â†’<details><summary>Production</summary><br>
   253â†’
   254â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for production deploys.
   255â†’
   256â†’Create a `.env.production` file.
   257â†’
   258â†’```sh
   259â†’$ echo "HELLO=production" > .env.production
   260â†’```
   261â†’
   262â†’Encrypt it.
   263â†’
   264â†’```sh
   265â†’$ dotenvx encrypt -f .env.production
   266â†’```
   267â†’
   268â†’Set `DOTENV_PRIVATE_KEY_PRODUCTION` (found in `.env.keys`) on your server.
   269â†’
   270â†’```
   271â†’$ heroku config:set DOTENV_PRIVATE_KEY_PRODUCTION=value
   272â†’```
   273â†’
   274â†’Commit your `.env.production` file to code and deploy.
   275â†’
   276â†’```
   277â†’$ git add .env.production
   278â†’$ git commit -m "encrypted .env.production"
   279â†’$ git push heroku main
   280â†’```
   281â†’
   282â†’Dotenvx will decrypt and inject the secrets at runtime using `dotenvx run -- node index.js`.
   283â†’
   284â†’</details>
   285â†’<details><summary>Syncing</summary><br>
   286â†’
   287â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to sync your .env files.
   288â†’
   289â†’Encrypt them with `dotenvx encrypt -f .env` and safely include them in source control. Your secrets are securely synced with your git.
   290â†’
   291â†’This still subscribes to the twelve-factor app rules by generating a decryption key separate from code.
   292â†’
   293â†’</details>
   294â†’<details><summary>More Examples</summary><br>
   295â†’
   296â†’See [examples](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples) of using dotenv with various frameworks, languages, and configurations.
   297â†’
   298â†’* [nodejs](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-nodejs)
   299â†’* [nodejs (debug on)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-nodejs-debug)
   300â†’* [nodejs (override on)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-nodejs-override)
   301â†’* [nodejs (processEnv override)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-custom-target)
   302â†’* [esm](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-esm)
   303â†’* [esm (preload)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-esm-preload)
   304â†’* [typescript](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-typescript)
   305â†’* [typescript parse](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-typescript-parse)
   306â†’* [typescript config](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-typescript-config)
   307â†’* [webpack](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-webpack)
   308â†’* [webpack (plugin)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-webpack2)
   309â†’* [react](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-react)
   310â†’* [react (typescript)](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-react-typescript)
   311â†’* [express](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-express)
   312â†’* [nestjs](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-nestjs)
   313â†’* [fastify](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-fastify)
   314â†’
   315â†’</details>
   316â†’
   317â†’&nbsp;
   318â†’
   319â†’## Agents
   320â†’
   321â†’<img src="https://dotenvx.com/assets/img/as2/9.jpg" height="400" alt="dotenvx-as2" align="right"/>
   322â†’
   323â†’> Software is changing, and dotenv must change with itâ€”that is why I built [agentic secret storage (AS2)](https://dotenvx.com/as2). Agents run code without humans at terminals, so plaintext `.env` files are the wrong primitive.
   324â†’>
   325â†’> AS2 is built for autonomous software: encrypted by default, zero console access, and cryptographyâ€‘first delivery that keeps operators out of the loop.
   326â†’>
   327â†’> It is backed by [Vestauth](https://github.com/vestauth/vestauth), the trusted, pioneering auth layer for agentsâ€”giving each agent a cryptographic identity so requests are signed with private keys and verified with public keys. No shared secrets to leak.
   328â†’>
   329â†’> It's what I'm using now. - [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   330â†’
   331â†’### Quickstart
   332â†’
   333â†’Install vestauth and initialize your agent.
   334â†’
   335â†’```bash
   336â†’npm i -g vestauth
   337â†’
   338â†’vestauth agent init
   339â†’```
   340â†’
   341â†’Your agent `set`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   342â†’
   343â†’```bash
   344â†’vestauth agent curl -X POST https://as2.dotenvx.com/set -d '{"KEY":"value"}'
   345â†’```
   346â†’
   347â†’And your agent `get`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   348â†’
   349â†’```bash
   350â†’vestauth agent curl "https://as2.dotenvx.com/get?key=KEY"
   351â†’```
   352â†’
   353â†’That's it! This new primitive unlocks secrets access for agents without human-in-the-loop, oauth flows, or API keys. It's the future for agents.
   354â†’
   355â†’&nbsp;
   356â†’
   357â†’## FAQ
   358â†’
   359â†’<details><summary>Should I commit my `.env` file?</summary><br/>
   360â†’
   361â†’No.
   362â†’
   363â†’Unless you encrypt it with [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx). Then we recommend you do.
   364â†’
   365â†’</details>
   366â†’<details><summary>What about variable expansion?</summary><br/>
   367â†’
   368â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx).
   369â†’
   370â†’</details>
   371â†’<details><summary>Should I have multiple `.env` files?</summary><br/>
   372â†’
   373â†’We recommend creating one `.env` file per environment. Use `.env` for local/development, `.env.production` for production and so on. This still follows the twelve factor principles as each is attributed individually to its own environment. Avoid custom set ups that work in inheritance somehow (`.env.production` inherits values form `.env` for example). It is better to duplicate values if necessary across each `.env.environment` file.
   374â†’
   375â†’> In a twelve-factor app, env vars are granular controls, each fully orthogonal to other env vars. They are never grouped together as â€œenvironmentsâ€‌, but instead are independently managed for each deploy. This is a model that scales up smoothly as the app naturally expands into more deploys over its lifetime.
   376â†’>
   377â†’> â€“ [The Twelve-Factor App](http://12factor.net/config)
   378â†’
   379â†’Additionally, we recommend using [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to encrypt and manage these.
   380â†’
   381â†’</details>
   382â†’
   383â†’<details><summary>How do I use dotenv with `import`?</summary><br/>
   384â†’
   385â†’Simply..
   386â†’
   387â†’```javascript
   388â†’// index.mjs (ESM)
   389â†’import 'dotenv/config' // see https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import
   390â†’import express from 'express'
   391â†’```
   392â†’
   393â†’A little background..
   394â†’
   395â†’> When you run a module containing an `import` declaration, the modules it imports are loaded first, then each module body is executed in a depth-first traversal of the dependency graph, avoiding cycles by skipping anything already executed.
   396â†’>
   397â†’> â€“ [ES6 In Depth: Modules](https://hacks.mozilla.org/2015/08/es6-in-depth-modules/)
   398â†’
   399â†’What does this mean in plain language? It means you would think the following would work but it won't.
   400â†’
   401â†’`errorReporter.mjs`:
   402â†’```js
   403â†’class Client {
   404â†’  constructor (apiKey) {
   405â†’    console.log('apiKey', apiKey)
   406â†’
   407â†’    this.apiKey = apiKey
   408â†’  }
   409â†’}
   410â†’
   411â†’export default new Client(process.env.API_KEY)
   412â†’```
   413â†’`index.mjs`:
   414â†’```js
   415â†’// Note: this is INCORRECT and will not work
   416â†’import * as dotenv from 'dotenv'
   417â†’dotenv.config()
   418â†’
   419â†’import errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs' // process.env.API_KEY will be blank!
   420â†’```
   421â†’
   422â†’`process.env.API_KEY` will be blank.
   423â†’
   424â†’Instead, `index.mjs` should be written as..
   425â†’
   426â†’```js
   427â†’import 'dotenv/config'
   428â†’
   429â†’import errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs'
   430â†’```
   431â†’
   432â†’Does that make sense? It's a bit unintuitive, but it is how importing of ES6 modules work. Here is a [working example of this pitfall](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-es6-import-pitfall).
   433â†’
   434â†’There are two alternatives to this approach:
   435â†’
   436â†’1. Preload with dotenvx: `dotenvx run -- node index.js` (_Note: you do not need to `import` dotenv with this approach_)
   437â†’2. Create a separate file that will execute `config` first as outlined in [this comment on #133](https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv/issues/133#issuecomment-255298822)
   438â†’</details>
   439â†’
   440â†’<details><summary>Can I customize/write plugins for dotenv?</summary><br/>
   441â†’
   442â†’Yes! `dotenv.config()` returns an object representing the parsed `.env` file. This gives you everything you need to continue setting values on `process.env`. For example:
   443â†’
   444â†’```js
   445â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   446â†’const variableExpansion = require('dotenv-expand')
   447â†’const myEnv = dotenv.config()
   448â†’variableExpansion(myEnv)
   449â†’```
   450â†’
   451â†’</details>
   452â†’<details><summary>What rules does the parsing engine follow?</summary><br/>
   453â†’
   454â†’The parsing engine currently supports the following rules:
   455â†’
   456â†’- `BASIC=basic` becomes `{BASIC: 'basic'}`
   457â†’- empty lines are skipped
   458â†’- lines beginning with `#` are treated as comments
   459â†’- `#` marks the beginning of a comment (unless when the value is wrapped in quotes)
   460â†’- empty values become empty strings (`EMPTY=` becomes `{EMPTY: ''}`)
   461â†’- inner quotes are maintained (think JSON) (`JSON={"foo": "bar"}` becomes `{JSON:"{\"foo\": \"bar\"}"`)
   462â†’- whitespace is removed from both ends of unquoted values (see more on [`trim`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/Trim)) (`FOO=  some value  ` becomes `{FOO: 'some value'}`)
   463â†’- single and double quoted values are escaped (`SINGLE_QUOTE='quoted'` becomes `{SINGLE_QUOTE: "quoted"}`)
   464â†’- single and double quoted values maintain whitespace from both ends (`FOO="  some value  "` becomes `{FOO: '  some value  '}`)
   465â†’- double quoted values expand new lines (`MULTILINE="new\nline"` becomes
   466â†’
   467â†’```
   468â†’{MULTILINE: 'new
   469â†’line'}
   470â†’```
   471â†’
   472â†’- backticks are supported (`` BACKTICK_KEY=`This has 'single' and "double" quotes inside of it.` ``)
   473â†’
   474â†’</details>
   475â†’<details><summary>What about syncing and securing .env files?</summary><br/>
   476â†’
   477â†’Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to unlock syncing encrypted .env files over git.
   478â†’
   479â†’</details>
   480â†’<details><summary>What if I accidentally commit my `.env` file to code?</summary><br/>
   481â†’
   482â†’Remove it, [remove git history](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/removing-sensitive-data-from-a-repository) and then install the [git pre-commit hook](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx#pre-commit) to prevent this from ever happening again. 
   483â†’
   484â†’```
   485â†’npm i -g @dotenvx/dotenvx
   486â†’dotenvx precommit --install
   487â†’```
   488â†’
   489â†’</details>
   490â†’<details><summary>What happens to environment variables that were already set?</summary><br/>
   491â†’
   492â†’By default, we will never modify any environment variables that have already been set. In particular, if there is a variable in your `.env` file which collides with one that already exists in your environment, then that variable will be skipped.
   493â†’
   494â†’If instead, you want to override `process.env` use the `override` option.
   495â†’
   496â†’```javascript
   497â†’require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   498â†’```
   499â†’
   500â†’</details>
   501â†’<details><summary>How can I prevent committing my `.env` file to a Docker build?</summary><br/>
   502â†’
   503â†’Use the [docker prebuild hook](https://dotenvx.com/docs/features/prebuild).
   504â†’
   505â†’```bash
   506â†’# Dockerfile
   507â†’...
   508â†’RUN curl -fsS https://dotenvx.sh/ | sh
   509â†’...
   510â†’RUN dotenvx prebuild
   511â†’CMD ["dotenvx", "run", "--", "node", "index.js"]
   512â†’```
   513â†’
   514â†’</details>
   515â†’<details><summary>How come my environment variables are not showing up for React?</summary><br/>
   516â†’
   517â†’Your React code is run in Webpack, where the `fs` module or even the `process` global itself are not accessible out-of-the-box. `process.env` can only be injected through Webpack configuration.
   518â†’
   519â†’If you are using [`react-scripts`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/react-scripts), which is distributed through [`create-react-app`](https://create-react-app.dev/), it has dotenv built in but with a quirk. Preface your environment variables with `REACT_APP_`. See [this stack overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42182577/is-it-possible-to-use-dotenv-in-a-react-project) for more details.
   520â†’
   521â†’If you are using other frameworks (e.g. Next.js, Gatsby...), you need to consult their documentation for how to inject environment variables into the client.
   522â†’
   523â†’</details>
   524â†’<details><summary>Why is the `.env` file not loading my environment variables successfully?</summary><br/>
   525â†’
   526â†’Most likely your `.env` file is not in the correct place. [See this stack overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42335016/dotenv-file-is-not-loading-environment-variables).
   527â†’
   528â†’Turn on debug mode and try again..
   529â†’
   530â†’```js
   531â†’require('dotenv').config({ debug: true })
   532â†’```
   533â†’
   534â†’You will receive a helpful error outputted to your console.
   535â†’
   536â†’</details>
   537â†’<details><summary>Why am I getting the error `Module not found: Error: Can't resolve 'crypto|os|path'`?</summary><br/>
   538â†’
   539â†’You are using dotenv on the front-end and have not included a polyfill. Webpack < 5 used to include these for you. Do the following:
   540â†’
   541â†’```bash
   542â†’npm install node-polyfill-webpack-plugin
   543â†’```
   544â†’
   545â†’Configure your `webpack.config.js` to something like the following.
   546â†’
   547â†’```js
   548â†’require('dotenv').config()
   549â†’
   550â†’const path = require('path');
   551â†’const webpack = require('webpack')
   552â†’
   553â†’const NodePolyfillPlugin = require('node-polyfill-webpack-plugin')
   554â†’
   555â†’module.exports = {
   556â†’  mode: 'development',
   557â†’  entry: './src/index.ts',
   558â†’  output: {
   559â†’    filename: 'bundle.js',
   560â†’    path: path.resolve(__dirname, 'dist'),
   561â†’  },
   562â†’  plugins: [
   563â†’    new NodePolyfillPlugin(),
   564â†’    new webpack.DefinePlugin({
   565â†’      'process.env': {
   566â†’        HELLO: JSON.stringify(process.env.HELLO)
   567â†’      }
   568â†’    }),
   569â†’  ]
   570â†’};
   571â†’```
   572â†’
   573â†’Alternatively, just use [dotenv-webpack](https://github.com/mrsteele/dotenv-webpack) which does this and more behind the scenes for you.
   574â†’
   575â†’</details>
   576â†’
   577â†’&nbsp;
   578â†’
   579â†’## Docs
   580â†’
   581â†’Dotenv exposes four functions:
   582â†’
   583â†’* `config`
   584â†’* `parse`
   585â†’* `populate`
   586â†’
   587â†’### Config
   588â†’
   589â†’`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590â†’[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591â†’and return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592â†’
   593â†’```js
   594â†’const result = dotenv.config()
   595â†’
   596â†’if (result.error) {
   597â†’  throw result.error
   598â†’}
   599â†’
   600â†’console.log(result.parsed)
   601â†’```
   602â†’
   603â†’You can additionally, pass options to `config`.
   604â†’
   605â†’#### Options
   606â†’
   607â†’##### path
   608â†’
   609â†’Default: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610â†’
   611â†’Specify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612â†’
   613â†’```js
   614â†’require('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615â†’```
   616â†’
   617â†’By default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618â†’
   619â†’Pass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620â†’
   621â†’```js  
   622â†’require('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623â†’```
   624â†’
   625â†’##### quiet
   626â†’
   627â†’Default: `false`
   628â†’
   629â†’Suppress runtime logging message.
   630â†’
   631â†’```js
   632â†’// index.js
   633â†’require('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634â†’console.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635â†’```
   636â†’
   637â†’```ini
   638â†’# .env
   639â†’HELLO=World
   640â†’```
   641â†’
   642â†’```sh
   643â†’$ node index.js
   644â†’[dotenv@17.0.0] injecting env (1) from .env
   645â†’Hello World
   646â†’```
   647â†’
   648â†’##### encoding
   649â†’
   650â†’Default: `utf8`
   651â†’
   652â†’Specify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653â†’
   654â†’```js
   655â†’require('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656â†’```
   657â†’
   658â†’##### debug
   659â†’
   660â†’Default: `false`
   661â†’
   662â†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663â†’
   664â†’```js
   665â†’require('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666â†’```
   667â†’
   668â†’##### override
   669â†’
   670â†’Default: `false`
   671â†’
   672â†’Override any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673â†’
   674â†’```js
   675â†’require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676â†’```
   677â†’
   678â†’##### processEnv
   679â†’
   680â†’Default: `process.env`
   681â†’
   682â†’Specify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683â†’
   684â†’```js
   685â†’const myObject = {}
   686â†’require('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687â†’
   688â†’console.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689â†’console.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690â†’```
   691â†’
   692â†’### Parse
   693â†’
   694â†’The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695â†’variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696â†’an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697â†’
   698â†’```js
   699â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700â†’const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701â†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702â†’console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703â†’```
   704â†’
   705â†’#### Options
   706â†’
   707â†’##### debug
   708â†’
   709â†’Default: `false`
   710â†’
   711â†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712â†’
   713â†’```js
   714â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715â†’const buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716â†’const opt = { debug: true }
   717â†’const config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718â†’// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719â†’```
   720â†’
   721â†’### Populate
   722â†’
   723â†’The engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724â†’
   725â†’For example, customizing the source:
   726â†’
   727â†’```js
   728â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729â†’const parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730â†’
   731â†’dotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732â†’
   733â†’console.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
   734â†’```
   735â†’
   736â†’For example, customizing the source AND target:
   737â†’
   738â†’```js
   739â†’const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   740â†’const parsed = { HELLO: 'universe' }
   741â†’const target = { HELLO: 'world' } // empty object
   742â†’
   743â†’dotenv.populate(target, parsed, { override: true, debug: true })
   744â†’
   745â†’console.log(target) // { HELLO: 'universe' }
   746â†’```
   747â†’
   748â†’#### options
   749â†’
   750â†’##### Debug
   751â†’
   752â†’Default: `false`
   753â†’
   754â†’Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755â†’
   756â†’##### override
   757â†’
   758â†’Default: `false`
   759â†’
   760â†’Override any environment variables that have already been set.
   761â†’
   762â†’&nbsp;
   763â†’
   764â†’## CHANGELOG
   765â†’
   766â†’See [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md)
   767â†’
   768â†’&nbsp;
   769â†’
   770â†’## Who's using dotenv?
   771â†’
   772â†’[These npm modules depend on it.](https://www.npmjs.com/browse/depended/dotenv)
   773â†’
   774â†’Projects that expand it often use the [keyword "dotenv" on npm](https://www.npmjs.com/search?q=keywords:dotenv).
